	rationale: "Sistemas financeiros têm tolerância zero a erro de centavo. Um bug que arredonda R$0,005 para baixo em 10.000 operações/mês: R$50/mês desaparecidos. Um bug que duplica liquidação: pagamento dobrado ao fornecedor. Um bug em scoring que classifica operação de alto risco como baixo risco: perda para o FIDC. OOI detecta problemas em produção (after the fact). TD cobre qualidade de código em geral. ML cobre design de modelos. Esta lens cobre como PROVAR CORREÇÃO ANTES DE PRODUÇÃO — reconciliação automática, property-based testing para invariantes financeiras, contract testing entre BCs, validação de decisões de agentes contra ground truth, e chaos engineering para failure modes. Na Mesh onde agentes IA tomam decisões financeiras (scoring, compliance) e processam fluxos monetários (antecipação, liquidação), testing não é quality assurance — é financial integrity infrastructure."
}

concepts: [
	{
		id:         "tv-financial-invariants"
		name:       "Invariantes Financeiras: Propriedades que NUNCA Podem Ser Violadas"
		nature:     "theoretical"
		role:       "framework"
		definition: "Invariante financeiro é uma propriedade do sistema que deve ser verdadeira em TODOS os estados, TODAS as transações, sem exceção. Violação de invariante = bug financeiro = perda de dinheiro ou violação regulatória. Invariantes fundamentais de contabilidade: (1) **conservation of money** — dinheiro não é criado nem destruído em transação. Soma de entradas = soma de saídas. Se operação de antecipação: valor cedido pelo fornecedor = valor pago pelo FIDC (menos deságio) + deságio retido pela plataforma. Total in = total out. (2) **double-entry consistency** — todo débito tem crédito correspondente. Ledger deve balancear: sum(débitos) = sum(créditos). Em qualquer momento: se não balanceia: bug. (3) **idempotency** — processar mesma operação 2x não duplica efeito financeiro. Se liquidação é executada, retry da mesma liquidação: no-op (não paga 2x). (4) **monotonic state progression** — operação financeira avança por estados sem retroceder ilegalmente. pendente → aprovada → liquidada → concluída. Não: concluída → pendente (sem operação explícita de estorno). (5) **precision preservation** — cálculos monetários não perdem precisão por arredondamento intermediário. R$100,00 ÷ 3 = R$33,33 + R$33,33 + R$33,34 (não R$33,33 × 3 = R$99,99 com R$0,01 perdido). Conceito de 'invariant-driven testing' (2023+): em vez de testar cenários específicos (dado input X, output deveria ser Y), testar propriedades que devem ser verdadeiras para QUALQUER input: 'para qualquer operação de antecipação: valor_cedido = valor_liquido + deságio.' Se propriedade viola para algum input: bug encontrado sem precisar enumerar todos os cenários."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, invariantes financeiras: (1) **conservation em antecipação:** valor_face_recebível = valor_liquido_fornecedor + deságio_fidc + taxa_plataforma. Para toda operação, em todo estado: soma dos componentes = valor original. Se ≠: bug. (2) **double-entry no ledger:** para toda entrada no ledger: existe entrada oposta de mesmo valor. Débito em conta do FIDC = crédito em conta da operação. Débito em conta da operação = crédito em conta do fornecedor. Balance check: sum(all_entries) = 0. Se ≠ 0: ledger inconsistente = bug. (3) **idempotency de liquidação:** se liquidação é processada e sistema recebe retry (network timeout → automatic retry): segunda execução detecta que liquidação já ocorreu → no-op. Se não: fornecedor recebe 2x. (4) **state machine validity:** operação em estado 'liquidada' não pode transicionar para 'pendente.' Transitions definidas em state machine. Tentativa de transição inválida: rejeitada com erro. (5) **precision:** todos os cálculos monetários em representação decimal (não floating point). BigDecimal ou integer de centavos (R$48.750,00 = 4875000 centavos). Nunca: float/double para dinheiro (0.1 + 0.2 ≠ 0.3 em IEEE 754). (6) **arredondamento justo:** quando divisão produz fração de centavo: regra explícita (round half-up, ou banker's rounding). Diferença alocada a componente explícito (plataforma absorve ou fornecedor recebe). Nunca: centavos desaparecem silenciosamente."
		meshImplication: "Invariant implementation: (1) **codify invariants** — cada invariante documentado no mesh-spec como assertion testável. invariant-001: 'para toda operação: valor_face = valor_liquido + deságio + taxa.' invariant-002: 'sum(ledger_entries) = 0 at all times.' invariant-003: 'para toda operação: process(op) seguido de process(op) = process(op).' (2) **test each invariant** — para cada invariante: property-based test (tv-property-based-testing) que gera operações aleatórias e verifica propriedade. Unit test com edge cases (valores de centavo, valores máximos, divisões que produzem fração). Integration test que verifica invariante end-to-end. (3) **runtime assertion** — em produção: after cada transação, assertion verifica invariantes. conservation check: if valor_face ≠ sum(components): log error + alert + block transaction. ledger balance check: periodic (every N minutes): if sum(entries) ≠ 0: alert critical. (4) **money representation** — NEVER float/double. Always: integer cents (R$48.750,00 = 4875000) or decimal type (BigDecimal in Kotlin, Decimal in Python). Database: NUMERIC(15,2) para BRL (até R$9.999.999.999.999,99). Application: consistent type across all layers (API → service → database). (5) **rounding rules** — documented: 'when calculation produces fractional centavo: round half-up. When splitting amount: allocate remainder to last component (or to platform fee).' Rules in code as reusable function: roundMoney(value, mode='HALF_UP'). Not: each developer implementing own rounding. (6) **CLAUDE.md for agents:** 'all monetary calculations use Money type (integer centavos). Never use float for money. Division that produces fraction: use roundMoney(). Invariant: valor_face = valor_liquido + deságio + taxa MUST hold after every calculation.' Anti-pattern: monetary calculation using float — 0.1 + 0.2 = 0.30000000000000004 in JavaScript. Over 10.000 operations: accumulated error = R$X.XX disappeared or appeared from nowhere. IEEE 754 floating point is incompatible with financial precision."
		rationale: "Invariant-driven testing 2023+. Double-entry accounting fundamentals. IEEE 754 floating point precision issues are well-documented. Na Mesh, conservation of money and double-entry consistency are the 2 non-negotiable invariants. Property-based testing proves them for arbitrary inputs, not just known test cases."
	},
	{
		id:         "tv-property-based-testing"
		name:       "Property-Based Testing: Provar Propriedades para Qualquer Input, Não Apenas Cenários Conhecidos"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "semi-annual"
		definition: "Traditional testing: developer writes specific test cases (given input X, expect output Y). Covers known scenarios. Misses unknown edge cases. Property-based testing (PBT, Claessen/Hughes 2000, QuickCheck): developer defines property ('for any valid operation: conservation holds'). Framework generates hundreds/thousands of random valid inputs. Verifies property for each. If property violated: reports minimal failing case (shrinking). Advantages for financial systems: (1) finds edge cases developer didn't imagine (amount = R$0.01, amount = R$9.999.999.999,99, deságio = 0%, deságio = 99.99%). (2) proves property holds for distribution of inputs, not just specific cases. (3) shrinking produces minimal reproducer (helpful for debugging). Conceito de 'generator design for financial data' (2024+): PBT quality depends on generator quality. Generator for operation: { valor: randomCurrency(0.01, 10_000_000.00), taxa: randomPercent(0.01, 99.99), prazo: randomDays(1, 365), score: randomInt(0, 100) }. Generator must produce: valid edge cases (minimum, maximum), invalid cases (negative, zero, overflow), and realistic distributions (most values mid-range with edge cases). Conceito de 'oracle' (testing): for financial invariant, oracle is the invariant itself. 'conservation: valor_face = valor_liquido + deságio + taxa.' No need for pre-computed expected output — property IS the oracle."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, PBT for financial invariants: (1) **conservation property:** forAll { op <- genOperation() }: op.valor_face == op.valor_liquido + op.deságio + op.taxa_plataforma. Generator: valor_face = randomCurrency(0.01, 10_000_000.00). Taxa = randomPercent(0.50, 5.00). Plataforma fee = randomPercent(0.10, 1.00). valor_liquido, deságio: derived by calculation. Assert: sum of parts = whole. Covers: centavos, large amounts, edge percentages, rounding scenarios. (2) **idempotency property:** forAll { op <- genOperation() }: process(op); process(op) == process(op). State after processing twice = state after processing once. Covers: all operation types, all amounts, network retry scenarios. (3) **state machine property:** forAll { transitions <- genTransitionSequence() }: every transition is valid per state machine definition. Invalid transitions: rejected. State after valid sequence: consistent. (4) **ledger balance property:** forAll { ops <- genOperationBatch(1, 100) }: after processing all ops: sum(ledger_entries) == 0. Covers: batches of 1-100 operations, various amounts, mixed types. (5) **scoring property:** forAll { features <- genFeatureSet() }: score(features) is in [0, 100] AND is deterministic (same features → same score). Does not test accuracy (that's backtesting) — tests consistency and bounds."
		meshImplication: "PBT implementation: (1) **framework:** Kotlin: kotest-property. Python: hypothesis. JavaScript: fast-check. Each: supports generators, shrinking, reproducible seeds. (2) **generators per domain type:** Money generator: range [0.01, 10_000_000.00], integer centavos internally. Percentage generator: range [0.01, 99.99], 2 decimal places. CNPJ generator: valid format + valid check digits. Date generator: business days only (exclude weekends, holidays — connects with temporal-modeling lens). Score generator: int [0, 100]. (3) **run count:** minimum 1000 iterations per property. For critical invariants (conservation, ledger balance): 10.000. CI: 1000 (fast). Nightly: 10.000 (thorough). (4) **seed persistence:** when PBT finds failure: seed is logged. Same seed reproduces same failure. Fix → re-run with same seed → verify fix. (5) **integration with CI:** property-based tests run in CI pipeline alongside unit tests. Failure: merge blocked. (6) **coverage of edge cases:** generators explicitly include: minimum (R$0.01), maximum (R$10M), zero (where valid), boundary values (score 0, 50, 100), rounding-trigger values (amounts that divide to fractional centavos). (7) **golden properties for Mesh:** document top 10 properties in mesh-spec. Each: name, description, generator, assertion. These are the financial constitution — immutable unless business rules change. Anti-pattern: 'we have 500 unit tests for the antecipação flow' — all with developer-chosen inputs. None test: R$0.01 antecipação (minimum), R$0 taxa (free?), R$9.999.999,99 (near overflow), taxa 0.001% (fractional centavo result). PBT with random generation: finds these edge cases automatically."
		dependsOn: ["tv-financial-invariants"]
		crossDependsOn: [{
			lensId:    "lens-ml-ai-systems-design"
			conceptId: "ml-model-versioning-reproducibility"
			context:   "ML defines model versioning and reproducibility — same input → same score with same model version. TV PBT tests this property: forAll { features }: score(features, model_v2.3) is deterministic. ML provides the model; TV proves its properties (determinism, bounded output, monotonicity where expected). ML is the system; TV proves its correctness."
		}]
		rationale: "Claessen/Hughes 2000: QuickCheck. Generator design 2024+. Na Mesh, PBT with 10.000 random operations proves conservation invariant holds across edge cases that no developer would enumerate manually. PBT found R$0.01 ÷ 3 = precision loss bug. Manual tests: never tested R$0.01."
	},
	{
		id:         "tv-reconciliation"
		name:       "Reconciliação Automática: Provar que o que o Sistema Diz Corresponde à Realidade"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "monthly"
		definition: "Reconciliação é o processo de comparar 2+ fontes de verdade e provar que concordam. Em sistemas financeiros: (1) **internal reconciliation** — sistema's own records agree with each other. Ledger entries balance. Operation total matches sum of line items. (2) **external reconciliation** — sistema's records agree with external source. Bank statement matches ledger. Tax records match operations. FIDC report matches carteira data. (3) **temporal reconciliation** — system's state at time T matches expected state based on operations processed up to T. End-of-day balance = opening balance + inflows - outflows. Conceito de 'continuous reconciliation' (2023+): não reconciliar 1x/mês (when discrepancy is found, 30 days of transactions to investigate). Reconciliar continuamente: after each transaction, after each batch, every hour, every day. Earlier detection = smaller scope of investigation. Conceito de 'reconciliation as test' (2024+): reconciliation checks are automated tests that run continuously. If discrepancy: alert (like test failure). Categories of discrepancy: (a) missing — record in source A but not in source B. (b) extra — record in source B but not in source A. (c) value mismatch — same record, different values. (d) status mismatch — same record, different status."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, reconciliation layers: (1) **ledger self-reconciliation:** every N minutes: sum(all_ledger_entries) == 0. If ≠ 0: critical alert. Investigação imediata. Significa: money appeared or disappeared in accounting. (2) **operation-ledger reconciliation:** for each operation: sum of ledger entries for this operation == 0 (internal balance). operation.valor_face == ledger entries that compose it (valor_liquido credit to fornecedor + deságio debit from FIDC + taxa credit to plataforma). (3) **bank statement reconciliation:** daily: compare expected bank movements (from system: operations liquidated today) with actual bank statement (from banking partner API or file). Match: by operation reference + amount. Discrepancies: missing (system says liquidated, bank doesn't show), extra (bank shows movement system doesn't know), value mismatch. (4) **FIDC carteira reconciliation:** for each FIDC: system's carteira (sum of active operations) matches FIDC's own records. Monthly: FIDC receives report → compares with own system → discrepancies flagged. Automated: if FIDC provides API: reconcile programmatically. (5) **scoring reconciliation (backtesting):** model predicted score X for operation. After N months: actual outcome (defaulted or not). Compare: predicted probability vs actual default rate. Calibration: if predicted 5% default and actual is 15%: model miscalibrated → retrain. (6) **event reconciliation:** for each command processed: expected events were emitted. Command 'approve operation' → events: OperationApproved, LedgerEntryCreated, NotificationSent. If any missing: system inconsistency."
		meshImplication: "Reconciliation implementation: (1) **ledger self-check:** scheduled job: every 15 minutes. Query: SELECT SUM(amount) FROM ledger_entries. If ≠ 0: alert severity critical + page on-call + halt new operations until resolved. This is the canary — if ledger doesn't balance: something is fundamentally broken. (2) **operation-component check:** after each operation state change: verify sum of components. post-approve: assert valor_face == valor_liquido + deságio + taxa. Failure: block state change, log error, alert. (3) **bank reconciliation:** daily batch job: fetch bank statement (API or SFTP file). For each system-generated expected payment: match in bank statement by reference + amount (±R$0.01 tolerance for bank rounding). Unmatched system records: 'expected but not yet in bank' (may be timing — retry next day). If unmatched after 3 days: escalate. Unmatched bank records: 'in bank but not in system' → investigate (manual deposit? Error?). Dashboard: reconciliation status per day. (4) **reconciliation report:** daily email/notification to finance team: 'Reconciliação D-1: 147 operações matched. 0 discrepancies. Ledger balance: R$0.00 ✓.' If discrepancies: detail with operation IDs and amounts. (5) **scoring backtesting:** monthly: for cohort of operations scored N months ago: compare predicted PD (probability of default) with actual default rate. Report: calibration chart (predicted vs actual by score band). If miscalibration >2 percentage points for any band: flag for model review. (6) **reconciliation as CI test:** subset of reconciliation logic runs in CI with synthetic data: process N operations → verify ledger balances → verify component conservation. If fails: merge blocked. Production reconciliation: runs on real data continuously. Anti-pattern: manual reconciliation at month-end by finance team downloading spreadsheets — discrepancy discovered on day 30 when 1000 operations are suspect. Continuous automated reconciliation: discrepancy discovered in 15 minutes when 1 operation is suspect."
		dependsOn: ["tv-financial-invariants"]
		crossDependsOn: [{
			lensId:    "lens-observability-operational-intelligence"
			conceptId: "ooi-sli-slo-error-budget"
			context:   "OOI defines SLIs/SLOs for system health. TV reconciliation defines financial SLIs: 'ledger balance = 0 (always)', 'bank reconciliation match rate > 99.9% daily', 'scoring calibration within 2pp of actual.' These are financial health SLIs — not response time or uptime, but monetary correctness. OOI provides the monitoring infrastructure; TV defines the financial health metrics that need monitoring."
		}]
		rationale: "Continuous reconciliation 2023+. Reconciliation as test 2024+. Na Mesh, ledger self-check every 15 minutes: discrepancy detected in minutes, not days. Bank reconciliation daily: match rate >99.9% expected. Any unmatched after 3 days: investigated. Financial health is continuously proven, not periodically checked."
	},
	{
		id:         "tv-contract-testing"
		name:       "Contract Testing entre Bounded Contexts: Interfaces que Nunca Quebram Silenciosamente"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "semi-annual"
		definition: "Contract testing verifica que producer (BC que expõe interface) e consumer (BC que consome) concordam sobre o contrato da interface — schema, semantics, behavior. Se producer muda schema (adiciona campo required, remove campo, muda tipo): contract test detecta ANTES de deploy, não quando consumer quebra em produção. Tipos: **(1) consumer-driven contract testing** (Pact, 2013+): consumer defines expectations ('I expect field X as string, field Y as integer'). Producer runs consumer's expectations against its implementation. If producer violates any consumer expectation: test fails. Consumer drives the contract — producer must satisfy all consumers. **(2) schema compatibility testing** (Confluent, 2020+): event schemas verified for backwards compatibility (new version must be readable by old consumers). Forward, backward, and full compatibility modes. **(3) API contract testing** (OpenAPI/AsyncAPI validation): API implementation verified against published specification. Request/response validated against schema. Conceito de 'contract as safety net for evolution' (2024+): contract tests enable safe evolution — producer can change internals freely as long as contract is preserved. Consumer is protected from breaking changes. In Mesh: ECL bounded context changes scoring algorithm internals → contract test verifies that ScoreCalculated event still has same schema → NGR consumer is unaffected."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, contract testing across BCs: (1) **ECL → NGR event contract:** ECL produces events (OperationApproved, ScoreCalculated). NGR consumes. Contract: event schema (fields, types, required/optional). Test: ECL schema change → verify NGR expectations still satisfied. If ECL removes field that NGR expects: test fails before deploy. (2) **ECL → FIDC reporting API contract:** ECL exposes API consumed by FIDC reporting. Contract: API response schema + semantics (field meanings, units, null behavior). Test: API change → verify FIDC reporting expectations. (3) **scoring service → ECL contract:** scoring service returns score + features + model_version. ECL expects: score (int 0-100), features (object), model_version (string semver). Test: if scoring service changes score to float or removes model_version: contract fails. (4) **Mesh → external banking API contract:** Mesh calls banking partner API for liquidação. Contract: request schema + expected response. Test: mock banking API with contract-defined responses. If banking API changes: contract defines expected behavior, mock updates, tests verify."
		meshImplication: "Contract testing implementation: (1) **event schema registry** — every event in event catalog (from EDA lens) has: schema definition (CUE, JSON Schema, or Avro). Schema registry validates: new version compatible with previous? Backward compatible: new schema can read old events (new fields optional, no removed required fields). (2) **Pact or equivalent** — for API contracts: consumer writes pact (expected request/response pairs). Provider verifies pact against implementation. CI: consumer PR runs consumer pact. Provider PR runs ALL consumer pacts. Provider change that breaks any consumer: blocked. (3) **schema evolution rules** — for events: (a) adding optional field: compatible (consumers ignore unknown fields). (b) adding required field: BREAKING — not allowed without consumer migration. (c) removing field: BREAKING. (d) changing field type: BREAKING. (e) renaming field: BREAKING (treat as remove old + add new). CI: schema compatibility check on every event schema change. (4) **contract test in CI** — every PR that changes: API response schema, event schema, inter-BC interface: contract tests run. Failure: merge blocked. Priority: same as unit tests (not optional, not 'nice-to-have'). (5) **contract for agent decisions** — scoring agent contract: input (feature set schema) → output (score schema: {score: int, model_version: string, features_used: string[], timestamp: datetime}). If agent output deviates from contract (missing field, wrong type): rejected by consumer. (6) **contract documentation** — each inter-BC contract in mesh-spec: producer, consumer, schema, compatibility rules, test location. Agente that modifies interface: check contract, run contract tests, update schema if needed. Anti-pattern: BCs communicate via shared database (no explicit contract). BC A changes column name → BC B breaks in production. No test caught it because there's no contract to test against."
		dependsOn: ["tv-financial-invariants"]
		crossDependsOn: [{
			lensId:    "lens-event-driven-architecture-patterns"
			conceptId: "eda-event-catalog"
			context:   "EDA defines event catalog as inventory of all events with schemas. TV contract testing uses catalog as the contract source: event schema in catalog IS the contract that producers must satisfy and consumers can rely on. EDA defines the catalog; TV proves that implementations conform to it. EDA is the specification; TV is the verification."
		}]
		rationale: "Pact 2013+. Schema compatibility Confluent 2020+. Contract as safety net 2024+. Na Mesh, ECL changing event schema without contract test: NGR breaks silently. With contract test: break detected in CI before deploy. Contract testing transforms evolution from 'scary change that might break consumers' to 'safe change verified against all consumers.'"
	},
	{
		id:         "tv-agent-decision-validation"
		name:       "Validação de Decisões de Agentes: Provar que IA Decide Corretamente"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "monthly"
		definition: "Agentes IA na Mesh tomam decisões com consequência financeira: scoring (determina taxa e aprovação), compliance (determina qualificação de fornecedor), alertas (determina se operação é flagged). Cada decisão deve ser validável contra ground truth ou business rules. Conceito de 'shadow mode / champion-challenger' (2023+): new model/agent runs in parallel with current (champion). Decisions compared. If challenger produces significantly different decisions: investigate before promoting. (1) **shadow mode:** challenger processes same inputs as champion. Output: logged but not acted upon. Comparison: are decisions aligned? Divergence report. (2) **champion-challenger A/B:** traffic split: 90% champion, 10% challenger. Both decisions acted upon. Compare outcomes over time. Better outcomes: promote challenger. (3) **backtesting:** apply new model to historical data with known outcomes. Compare: model's predictions vs actual outcomes. Calibration, discrimination (AUROC), precision, recall. Conceito de 'decision audit' (2024+): for each agent decision: record input, model version, output, confidence, features used. After outcome is known (operation defaulted or not): compare decision vs outcome. Aggregate: decision quality metrics per model version, per time period, per segment."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, agent validation: (1) **scoring validation:** new scoring model (v2.4) before deployment: backtesting — apply v2.4 to last 6 months of operations with known outcomes. Compare: v2.4 scores vs actual default. Metrics: AUROC (discrimination), calibration (predicted PD vs actual), precision at approval threshold. If v2.4 AUROC > v2.3 AND calibration within 2pp: promote. If not: investigate. (2) **scoring shadow mode:** v2.4 runs in shadow: every new operation scored by both v2.3 (production) and v2.4 (shadow). Log: {operation_id, score_v2.3, score_v2.4, delta}. Dashboard: distribution of deltas. If >20% of operations have delta >10 points: significant divergence → investigate before promoting. (3) **compliance validation:** compliance agent checks documents against requirements. Validation: human sample review. Monthly: 50 random compliance decisions → human reviews same documents → agreement rate. Target: >95% agreement. If <90%: compliance agent is miscalibrated. (4) **alert validation:** alert agent flags anomalous operations. Validation: precision (of flagged operations, how many were genuinely anomalous?) and recall (of genuinely anomalous operations, how many were flagged?). Monthly review of flagged operations: 'was this flag correct?' False positive rate: target <20%. False negative: target <5% (critical — missed anomaly is worse than false alarm)."
		meshImplication: "Agent validation implementation: (1) **decision log** — every agent decision: {decision_id, agent_type, model_version, input_features: {...}, output: {score, decision, confidence}, timestamp, org_context}. Immutable. Retained for backtesting (years). Schema: standardized across agent types. (2) **outcome tracking** — for each scored operation: after 30/60/90/180 days: actual status (performing, late, defaulted). Link: decision_id → outcome. Enables: retrospective calibration analysis. (3) **backtesting pipeline** — automated: new model version → run against historical data → produce metrics report → compare with current version → flag if degradation. Can be triggered by: new model version, periodic schedule (monthly), or manual request. (4) **shadow mode infrastructure** — API/service: accepts operation → routes to champion + challenger → champion result returned to caller → challenger result logged. Comparison job: daily aggregate of champion vs challenger divergence. Dashboard: delta distribution, divergence %, by score band. (5) **human review sampling** — compliance: random 50 operations/month selected for human review. Blind: reviewer doesn't see agent's decision before own assessment. Compare: agreement rate. Statistical significance: 50 samples gives ±10% confidence at 95%. More for tighter bounds. (6) **promotion criteria** — document in mesh-spec: 'scoring model promotion requires: backtesting AUROC > current by ≥0.5%, calibration within 2pp across all score bands, shadow mode divergence <15% after 2 weeks.' Not: 'it looks better.' Quantitative criteria, documented, automated. (7) **regression detection** — production monitoring: rolling calibration (predicted PD vs actual, 30-day window). If calibration degrades >3pp from baseline: alert → investigate → potential revert to previous version. (8) **for agents generating code (Claude Code):** validation is different — output is code, not decision. Validation: CI tests (unit + property-based + contract + isolation). Code review by human for business logic. The code agent's 'decisions' are validated by the test suite it generates AND by the test suite that pre-exists. Anti-pattern: deploy new scoring model based on backtesting alone, without shadow mode. Backtesting uses historical data — may not reflect current distribution. Shadow mode catches distribution drift that backtesting misses."
		dependsOn: ["tv-financial-invariants", "tv-reconciliation"]
		crossDependsOn: [{
			lensId:    "lens-ai-agent-governance"
			conceptId: "aag-hitl-calibration"
			context:   "AAG defines HITL calibration — when human reviews agent decisions. TV agent validation defines HOW to validate: backtesting (historical accuracy), shadow mode (live comparison), human sampling (random blind review), production monitoring (rolling calibration). AAG says 'human must verify agent decisions above threshold'; TV says 'here's how to systematically verify decision quality: quantitative criteria, automated pipelines, documented promotion gates.' AAG is the governance principle; TV is the validation methodology."
