	{
		id:         "tv-test-strategy-by-layer"
		name:       "Estratégia de Testes por Camada: Pirâmide com Emphasis em Invariantes"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "semi-annual"
		definition: "Test pyramid (Cohn 2009): many unit tests (fast, isolated) → fewer integration tests (slower, real dependencies) → fewest e2e tests (slowest, full system). For financial systems: modified pyramid with financial emphasis: **(1) unit tests** — business logic: money calculations, state machine transitions, validation rules, scoring functions. Fast. Isolated. Cover all edge cases. Run on every build. **(2) property-based tests** — financial invariants: conservation, idempotency, ledger balance, state machine validity. Random inputs. Run on every build (1000 iterations) + nightly (10.000). **(3) contract tests** — inter-BC interfaces: event schemas, API contracts. Run on every build. Detect integration issues without running full system. **(4) integration tests** — real database, real event bus, real API calls between services (within test environment). Reconciliation tests. Tenant isolation tests. Run on every build (subset) + nightly (full). **(5) e2e tests** — full workflow: create fornecedor → submit operation → score → approve → liquidate → reconcile. Run nightly or per-deploy. Slow but comprehensive. **(6) agent validation tests** — backtesting pipeline, shadow comparison, human review sampling. Run: per model version + monthly. Conceito de 'test confidence for financial systems' (2024+): test suite must give confidence level: 'I can deploy with confidence that: money calculations are correct (property-based), interfaces are compatible (contract), system processes correctly end-to-end (e2e), and agent decisions are calibrated (validation).' Missing any layer: confidence gap."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, test strategy: (1) **unit (run: every build, <2 min):** money arithmetic (roundMoney, splitAmount, calculateTaxa). State machine transitions (valid + invalid). Validation rules (CNPJ format, amount range, date validity). Score calculation (deterministic, bounded). ~200-500 tests at MVP. (2) **property-based (run: every build 1k, nightly 10k):** conservation invariant. Idempotency invariant. Ledger balance invariant. State machine completeness. Score determinism + bounds. ~10-20 properties. (3) **contract (run: every build, <1 min):** ECL event schemas vs NGR expectations. API response schemas vs consumer expectations. Scoring service output vs ECL expectations. ~20-50 contract tests at MVP. (4) **integration (run: every build subset, nightly full, <10 min):** operation flow: create → approve → liquidate with real PostgreSQL + real event bus. Tenant isolation: cross-tenant access denied (from MT lens). Reconciliation: ledger balance after N operations. ~50-100 integration tests. (5) **e2e (run: nightly or per-deploy, <30 min):** complete happy path: fornecedor creates operation → construtora approves → FIDC funds → liquidation → reconciliation. Complete error paths: reject, cancel, timeout, duplicate. ~10-20 e2e scenarios. (6) **agent validation (run: per model + monthly):** backtesting, shadow comparison, human sample review. ~3-5 validation pipelines."
		meshImplication: "Test strategy implementation: (1) **CI pipeline structure:** PR build: unit + property (1k) + contract + integration (subset) + tenant isolation. Time: <5 minutes. Failure: merge blocked. Nightly: property (10k) + integration (full) + e2e (all scenarios). Time: <30 minutes. Failure: alert team. (2) **coverage targets:** unit: >90% line coverage for financial calculation modules. Property: 100% of documented invariants have property test. Contract: 100% of inter-BC interfaces have contract test. Integration: 100% of critical paths (happy + primary error paths). E2e: top 5 user workflows. (3) **test data management:** synthetic data generators: reusable across test types. Generators: valid operations, valid fornecedores, valid construtoras with realistic distributions. Shared: unit, property, integration, e2e use same generators (configured differently). (4) **flaky test zero-tolerance** — flaky test (passes sometimes, fails sometimes): treated as bug. Investigate. Fix. If intermittent: isolate cause (timing, concurrency, test order dependency). Financial system cannot tolerate 'sometimes passes' — that means 'sometimes money is wrong.' (5) **mutation testing (optional, advanced)** — after high unit coverage: mutation testing verifies test quality. Mutate code (change + to -, remove condition): tests should fail. If mutant survives (tests don't catch): test gap identified. For financial calculations: mutation survival rate target <5%. (6) **test for agents:** CLAUDE.md: 'when implementing financial logic: write property-based test for invariants. When modifying inter-BC interface: run contract tests. When creating new endpoint: add tenant isolation test. Minimum: unit test for every function that touches Money type.' Anti-pattern: 100% line coverage but 0 property-based tests — all tests are 'given R$1000 at 2.5% for 30 days: expect R$979.17.' Tests pass. But: R$0.01 at 99.99% for 1 day → precision loss → no test catches it. Line coverage ≠ edge case coverage."
