	{
		id:         "tv-chaos-and-failure-testing"
		name:       "Chaos Engineering e Failure Testing: O que Acontece Quando as Coisas Quebram"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "quarterly"
		definition: "Chaos engineering (Netflix 2011, Principles of Chaos Engineering 2018): deliberately inject failures to verify system handles them correctly. For financial systems: failure handling is critical — partial failure that leaves money in inconsistent state is worse than clean failure that rolls back. Concepto de 'financial failure modes' (2024+): (1) **network failure mid-transaction** — bank API call succeeds but response is lost. System doesn't know if payment was made. Retry: might double-pay. Don't retry: might not pay. Solution: idempotency key + reconciliation. (2) **partial batch failure** — 50 operations approved in batch. 48 succeed, 2 fail (validation, timeout). What happens to the 2? Retried? Rolled back? Reported? (3) **database failure during write** — ledger entry partially written. On recovery: is ledger consistent? Solution: transaction isolation (ACID). (4) **event loss** — operation approved, event published, consumer doesn't receive (broker failure). System: operation is approved. Consumer: doesn't know. Solution: outbox pattern, event replay. (5) **clock skew** — 2 services with different clock readings. Timestamps disagree. Settlement date calculated differently. Solution: NTP synchronization, UTC everywhere, tolerance for small skew."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, chaos scenarios to test: (1) **bank API timeout after sending payment** — test: inject timeout after sending POST to bank API. Verify: system records 'payment sent, response unknown.' Reconciliation: next bank statement check matches. No duplicate payment on retry (idempotency key). (2) **database failure during ledger write** — test: inject database failure mid-transaction. Verify: no partial ledger entries (transaction rolled back). Ledger balance unchanged. Operation status: unchanged (not partially updated). (3) **event broker unavailable** — test: stop event broker during operation approval. Verify: transactional outbox captures event. When broker recovers: event delivered. Consumer receives event (possibly delayed). No lost events. (4) **scoring service timeout** — test: inject timeout in scoring service. Verify: operation goes to 'scoring failed' status (not 'scored with default value'). Retry logic: attempts N times with backoff. After N failures: alert + manual review queue. (5) **concurrent approval race condition** — test: 2 simultaneous approve requests for same operation. Verify: exactly 1 succeeds (optimistic locking or database constraint). Other: receives conflict response. No duplicate approval. No inconsistent state."
		meshImplication: "Chaos testing implementation: (1) **staged approach** — don't start with production chaos. Stage 1: chaos in integration tests (inject failures in test environment). Stage 2: chaos in staging (inject in environment that mirrors production). Stage 3 (mature): chaos in production with safeguards (feature flags, automatic rollback). For Mesh MVP: Stage 1 only. (2) **failure injection mechanisms** — test environment: mock/stub external dependencies (bank API, event broker) with configurable failure modes (timeout, error, partial success). Framework: toxiproxy (network failures), testcontainers (database failure simulation), custom mocks (API failure). (3) **verify correct failure handling** — for each chaos scenario: define expected behavior BEFORE injecting failure. 'When bank API times out: system records unknown status, schedules reconciliation, does not retry payment without idempotency check.' Run scenario. Verify expected behavior. If different: fix handling, not just test. (4) **runbook per failure mode** — for each known failure: documented runbook in mesh-spec. Runbook: what happens, what system does automatically, what human must do if automated recovery fails. Example: 'Bank API timeout: system records unknown. Automated: next reconciliation cycle (15 min) checks bank. If matched: status updated. If not matched after 3 cycles: alert finance team. Manual: verify with bank, update status manually.' (5) **game days** — quarterly: simulate failure scenario. Team walks through: automated response, monitoring alerts, manual runbook. Verify: runbook is current, monitoring works, team knows what to do. Not chaos in production — tabletop exercise. (6) **idempotency as foundation** — every operation that touches money: idempotent. Idempotency key: unique per operation attempt. System checks: 'have I processed this key before?' If yes: return cached result. If no: process and store result with key. Prevents: double payment, double approval, double ledger entry. Implementation: idempotency_key column in operations table with unique constraint. Anti-pattern: no failure testing until production incident → scramble to fix → patch handling → no test added → same failure class occurs again. Proactive chaos: find failures before users do."
		dependsOn: ["tv-financial-invariants", "tv-reconciliation"]
		rationale: "Netflix 2011: chaos engineering. Financial failure modes 2024+. Na Mesh, bank API timeout is inevitable (networks fail). Question is not 'will it happen?' but 'when it happens, does the system handle it correctly?' Chaos testing: proves handling BEFORE production failure occurs."
	},
